of a census decreed by Caesar Augustus She treasured them and pondered them in her heart Shepherds Glory to God in the highest, and on earth peace A sword would pierce her own soul also He had seen God''s salvation with his own eyes They recognize and testify to the significance of the child Jesus He truly grew through ordinary human development while remaining unique He is salvation prepared for all peoples, including Gentiles They fit Luke''s pattern of God''s favor reaching the lowly and ordinary It reveals his unique relation to the Father even in childhood The emperor''s census becomes the means by which God''s saving plan unfolds in Bethlehem He is announced as Savior and Lord yet lies in a manger and grows in an ordinary family It widens the testimony to Jesus across heaven, humble hearers, and devout Israel She adds a second temple witness of praise and expectation around redemption It shows his unique sonship and wisdom while he still submits to his parents He is Israel''s glory and also light for revelation to the Gentiles The Savior is born in lowliness yet recognized as God''s promised salvation Angels, shepherds, Simeon, Anna, and finally the family setting all answer revelation with praise and wonder Even here Luke hints that Jesus is oriented around the Father''s affairs above all else Jesus is recognized early as Savior, yet his path unfolds through humility, misunderstanding, and growth They questioned whether he might be the Christ A baptism of repentance for the forgiveness of sins Do not extort and be content with your wages Collect no more than appointed Fruits worthy of repentance The Holy Spirit in bodily form like a dove The Holy Spirit and fire You are my beloved Son; in you I am well pleased He was praying and heaven was opened A winnowing fork separating wheat from chaff It marks Jesus publicly and concretely for Spirit-filled mission It places Jesus in solidarity with all humanity, not Israel alone Repentance is shown in concrete ethical fruit, not mere ancestry or ritual He warns that ancestry without repentance cannot save them from coming wrath It closes off John''s role and clears the stage for Jesus''s ministry The forerunner prepares repentant expectation, and the beloved Son is publicly revealed to begin the mission It links him not only to Israel''s story but back to Adam and humanity as a whole Jesus''s baptism is marked by prayer at the moment heaven opens and the Spirit descends The chapter warns of coming wrath while announcing the Spirit-anointed Son Luke keeps Israel''s promises intact while also widening Jesus''s significance to all humanity John calls for repentance, the Father identifies the Son, and the genealogy frames Jesus in salvation history Jesus is identified as God''s beloved Son and linked to Adam just before entering wilderness testing John''s ethical call prepares for the beloved Son whose genealogy locates him in God''s long redemptive story It is marked by repentance and fruit, not reliance on ancestry alone It sharply distinguishes the forerunner from the far greater one who is coming Scripture They said Jesus was the Son of God In his hometown In the wilderness Simon''s They were filled with wrath and tried to throw him down The Scripture he had just read Isaiah''s prophecy about good news and liberty To show that God''s mercy had reached outsiders when Israel was unbelieving He was sent for that purpose Jesus''s word has immediate authority over spiritual and physical brokenness He defines his mission as Spirit-anointed good news, liberty, and healing They rejected his claim of fulfillment and were angered by examples of grace to Gentiles His ministry flows from Spirit-empowered obedience after the wilderness testing It foreshadows how prophetic grace can be resisted even by those most familiar with Jesus The obedient Son resists the devil and then publicly declares the shape of his mission Jesus declares good news in Scripture and then enacts it through deliverance and healing He teaches with authority and commands demons and sickness alike He is Spirit-anointed, scripturally grounded, resisted by some, and authoritative over evil It exposes that God''s mercy cannot be controlled by hometown privilege or ethnic presumption It introduces the Spirit, Scripture fulfillment, opposition, and mission to the needy and outsiders The beloved Son proves his identity through obedient dependence and proclamation of the Father''s liberating purpose Spirit-led mission, prophetic fulfillment, rejection, and powerful ministry all appear together He embraces obedience to the Father rather than power, spectacle, or compromise His mission continues under divine purpose and cannot be ended on the crowd''s terms Simon''s boat Through the roof on a bed He touched him and said, ''I will; be clean'' From now on you will catch people He left everything and followed him The bridegroom''s presence changes the time for fasting The sick, not the healthy Show himself to the priest and offer as Moses commanded Jesus ate with tax collectors and sinners Levi Jesus''s ministry brings a new reality that old structures cannot simply contain unchanged Public power in ministry is matched by hidden dependence on the Father The miraculous catch exposes Jesus''s holy authority and Peter''s unworthiness It shows Jesus deliberately calls socially compromised outsiders into discipleship Jesus''s holiness overcomes uncleanness rather than being defiled by it Jesus''s gracious acts reveal divine authority and simultaneously provoke resistance He has authority to forgive, power to heal, and the right to call followers into a new way of life The Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins God''s kingdom welcomes repentant sinners into restored fellowship It displays Jesus drawing very different kinds of needy people into one circle of mercy and call Jesus''s authority is exercised from a place of communion with the Father even as opposition intensifies Jesus gathers followers by extending holy mercy to the unclean and the socially excluded He gathers disciples by cleansing, forgiving, healing, and eating with the very people others avoid Leave all, trust his word, receive cleansing and forgiveness, and join his mission Calling begins with awareness of Jesus''s holiness and one''s own unworthiness, answered by grace He prayed to God A man building a house on rock A withered right hand Blessings and woes On a level place He asked whether it is lawful to do good or to do harm Twelve Love your enemies and do good to those who hate you A speck Offer the other also A person''s inner character is revealed by outward words and actions Hypocritical, self-blind condemnation rather than all moral discernment God''s kingdom reverses ordinary human evaluations of security and success They reveal the kingdom''s reversal of ordinary values and securities It shows the formation of the apostolic community arises from prayerful dependence Both reveal Jesus''s authority to interpret life under God''s kingdom and expose hardened religion As reflecting the Father''s character in generosity, forgiveness, and non-retaliation Kingdom disciples are prayer-formed, enemy-loving, self-aware, fruitful hearers who act on Jesus''s words Hearing Jesus is insufficient without doing what he says Jesus forms a community before giving the ethic that will shape it The call to mercy, love of enemies, and generosity flows from the Father''s own mercy and kindness Blessedness is tied to life under God''s future reign, not merely present comfort or status It combines prayer, enemy-love, mercy, discernment, and obedient practice He authoritatively interprets Sabbath, forms a people, and teaches the life of the kingdom It shows kingdom teaching demands embodied obedience that can withstand judgment and trial His faith Young man, I tell you, arise Nain A sinful woman A centurion''s servant Tell John what you have seen and heard: the blind receive sight and the poor have 